flowRoot.flowPara: We analyze trends in mortality for three large age groups from 1990 to 2010 for all 32 Mexican states, and compare these with a low mortality benchmark. We assess the impact of avoidable mortality on survival at the state level by sex. We find improvements in survival for the population aged 0 to 14 mainly caused amenable to medical service. The adult population aged 15 to 39 shows deterioration among males after 2006 in almost every state. Adults aged 40 to 74 show an unexpected decrease in the low mortality benchmark, indicating universal deterioration in survival with large variations between states.

The low mortality benchmark is calculated in the basis of the lowest observed mortality rates by age, cause of death, from among all states for a given sex and year. It has a unique age profile, and determines our benchmark survival. It can be treated as the best presently achievable mortality assuming perfect difussion of the best available practices and technologies within a set of populations.

We smooth cause-specific death rates over time for each state and sex separately using 2-d-p-spline method proposed by Camarda (2012). We calculate the average years lived in each age group (temporary life expectancy) and estimate cause-specific contributions to the difference between state-specific temporary life expectancy and the low mortality benchmark. We use standard decomposition methods (Horiuchi et al. 2008).
Official deaths microdata from Mexican Statistical Office (INEGI) and population estimates from the Mexican Society of Demography from 1990 to 2010.

Survival among the young shows convergence and improvements towards the low mortality benchmark, approaching near-complete survival between ages 0-14. However, both males and females have lagged begind in sates suchas Puebla, Tlaxcala and Mxico.
Reductions in mortality rates from causes amenable to medical service account for the increase in survival and convergence towards the best mortalitypattern in every state

text.tspan: Deviations in avoidable causes of death in adulthood
drive mortality inequality between Mexican states

flowRoot.flowPara: Survival between 15 and 39 shows a common shift after 2005 in almost every state in Mexico. Deviations from the low mortality benchmark were mainly driven by homicide mortality. The unexpected increase of homicide led to widening the gap between benchmark and observed survival. In the Northern region, the gap went from around a quarter of year in 2002 to more than one year by 2010 in Sinaloa, Durango and Chihuahua.

Survival between ages 40 and 75 years shows stagnation and deterioration during the entire period. Even the low mortality benchmark exhibits a gradual downward trend, pointing to increases in adult mortality in every state. From a potential maximum of 35 years, all states are living on average less than 30 years for males and 32 for males.

flowRoot.flowPara: Medically amenable causes of death still contribute to the gap between survival and the low mortality benchmark. However, improvements in this category throughout the period 1990-2010 helped reduce deviations in almost every state. Opposing this, the increase of diabetes mortality, ischemic heart diseases and cirrhosis contribute significantly to the difference between the observed and the best mortality. On the contrary, cirrhosis affects male survival mainly in the Central and Southern regions. Homicide mortality also affects older-adult survival in particular states.
Nearly every state in the North could gain more than one year of life if IHD mortality were reduced to the low mortality benchmark.
